  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Specifically, researchers must use open-source LLMs that clearly document their underlying training data and/or provide a clear time-stamp beyond which the LLM has not been updated, such as the Llama family of models (Touvron et al., 2023; Dubey et al., 2024) or the StoriesLM family (Sarkar, 2024).",
    "Having made such a choice, the LLM can provide a tremendous advantage for prediction tasks using text.",
    "Predicting economic variables from text requires modeling the complex structure and semantics of language, which requires vast amounts of training data.",
    "Since open-source LLMs have already been pre-trained on large corpuses to learn this structure, they can serve as foundations upon which researchers can form accurate predictions from even fairly small datasets.",
    "Our second result relates to estimation problems, in which the researcher wants to relate some economic concept (e.g., positive or negative news, hawkish attitudes, or policy topic) expressed in text in order to estimate some downstream economic parameter."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Specifically, researchers must use open-source LLMs that clearly document their underlying training data and/or provide a clear time-stamp beyond which the LLM has not been updated, such as the Llama family of models (Touvron et al., 2023; Dubey et al., 2024) or the StoriesLM family (Sarkar, 2024)."
